course_description:
The focus of this course is predominantly on the external financial statement audit, within the framework of assurance. However, auditing is multidisciplinary in nature, requiring and integrating knowledge of business, accounting, information systems, law and strategy.

Students who have yet to complete ACCT201A Corporate Reporting & Analysis of Financial Statements, ACCT203 Accounting Information Systems and ACCT206 Governance, Risk and Assurance, are strongly advised not to sign up for this course. Students without this necessary prior knowledge will be responsible for acquiring the knowledge on their own.

This course focuses on the audit of financial statements by the external auditor, and is designed to:

1. provide students with an in-depth knowledge and understanding of key auditing and assurance concepts and methodologies;

2. develop the skills and attitudes necessary for providing financial statement audits and other assurance services, including problem-solving and decision making, critical thinking, communication, teamwork, interpersonal skills and professional values and ethics;

3. develop analytical, strategic and systems thinking through the merging and melding of information from related disciplines;

4. inculcate in students an attitude of active learning at both individual and team level, through students  pre-seminar preparation, involvement in seminar discussions, seminar activities and project work; and

5. develop the mindset and values required to succeed in the profession.

This module provides students with an insight into the theory and practice of accounting and governance. Specifically, the course aims to provide:

  An overview of the financial reporting process;
  An overview of how accounting information is used for valuation purposes and contracting purposes;
  An overview of earnings management   causes, tools, and consequences;
  An overview of other corporate governance mechanisms, including the board of directors and internal control.

In each of the above areas, we will discuss both the insights learned from research and the practices.

